, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Colette, Francois, Noemie.","French: habitational name from (Les) Monceaux, the name of several places in the northern part of France, derived from Late Latin <i>monticellum</i> ‘little mountain’, a diminutive of <i>mons</i> ‘mountain’, genitive <i>montis</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Moncion","meanings":["Hispanic (Dominican Republic; <b>Monción</b>): of French origin, most likely a derivative of Late Latin <i>monticellum</i> ‘little mountain’ (see   Monceaux  ). The surname <i>Moncion</i>, which is virtually non-existing in France, is also found in Haiti."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Monceaux was born in 1150, in Herstmonceux, Sussex, England, United Kingdom as the son of Leland De Hurst DeMonceaux. He had at least 1 son. He died in 1200, in his hometown, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1150–1200":"1150–1200","–Male":"Surnud","1112–1150":"1112–1150","1200":"1200","1112":"1112","1150":"1150","Herstmonceaux Castle, Sussex, England":"Herstmonceux, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Herstmonceaux, Sussex, England":"Herstmonceux, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1150–1200":"1150–1200","–Male":"Kuollut","1112–1150":"1112–1150","1200":"1200","1112":"1